<div id="review_1911592479" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1911592479" />
    <a title="Josef" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/48071287-josef"><img alt="Josef" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1911592479?book_show_action=true">Feb 12, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Josef" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Josef" href="/user/show/48071287-josef">Josef</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1911592479" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2983762883990585434">I have read this book for my African Literature Graduation Project. To be honest, I might have made the wrong choice. Anthills of The Savannah is a disappointment for someone who&apos;s read Things fall apart, since It is more like collected articles than a novella. Achebe used a set of technics which, personally, I couldn&apos;t find neccessary for producing a neat piece of literature. First, a loused up shift between POVs with multi-oriented storytelling order. At times we find ourselves implementing ir</span>
  <span id="freeText2983762883990585434" style="display:none">I have read this book for my African Literature Graduation Project. To be honest, I might have made the wrong choice. Anthills of The Savannah is a disappointment for someone who's read Things fall apart, since It is more like collected articles than a novella. Achebe used a set of technics which, personally, I couldn't find neccessary for producing a neat piece of literature. First, a loused up shift between POVs with multi-oriented storytelling order. At times we find ourselves implementing ironic presentations of the characters according to Chris's point of view who's not the only protagonist, other times Ikem takes on the narration and starts flash backs which have no value to the development of the plot; which I find very boring. However, I think that the plot starts to get a little be interesting at chapter 12 after the suspension of Ikem from The National Gazette newspaper. I mean ... Mr. Achebe for God's sake you could have started from there and made it a short storty instead of boring monologues full of political jargon.<br /><br />Anyway I am mad, I don't like what I've just read. Sorry Mr. Achebe,RIP, but I'll talk to my supervisor to save me from this mess.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2983762883990585434" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


