        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3746044915" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15727754475535627438">I wavered considerably in rating this book. In sections it was brilliant and moving, but the book as a whole failed to gel; neither its characters, its plot, its ideas nor its mythology moved me. Perhaps it wasn&apos;t meant to, as per the statement by Ikem, &quot;Writers don&apos;t give prescriptions. They give headaches.&quot; Or perhaps it simply was not written for me.<br/><br/>That said, the opening chapter of the cabinet meeting, in which the leader dominates, manipulates and humiliates his Secretaries and Commissioner</span>
  <span id="freeText15727754475535627438" style="display:none">I wavered considerably in rating this book. In sections it was brilliant and moving, but the book as a whole failed to gel; neither its characters, its plot, its ideas nor its mythology moved me. Perhaps it wasn't meant to, as per the statement by Ikem, "Writers don't give prescriptions. They give headaches." Or perhaps it simply was not written for me.<br /><br />That said, the opening chapter of the cabinet meeting, in which the leader dominates, manipulates and humiliates his Secretaries and Commissioners, is wonderful, and I loved the speech made by Ikem to the students and their subsequent questions and answers. I also enjoyed the meeting of Ikem and the delegation from Abazon and the chapters detailing Chris's journey to Abazon. <br /><br />However, the female characters did not come to life for me at all, and I could not see any life or passion in their relationships with the male characters. I also struggled with the portions of dialogue in dialect and I wondered what I missed.<br /><br />I was mystified by Nadine Gordimer's over the top praise for the novel in her NYT Book Review. <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.nytimes.com/1988/02/21/books/a-tyranny-of-clowns.html?pagewanted=all">https://www.nytimes.com/1988/02/21/bo...</a><br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
